Here's the optimized Java code that counts the occurrences of recurrent entities in an integer array. It also includes error handling to manage invalid data types. This implementation uses a `HashMap` to store the counts of each element, making it efficient and straightforward.

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class MainClass {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Object[] designatedSet = {1, 2, 3, 2, 'a', 4, 5, 2, 4, 5, 5}; // Using Object array to allow mixed types
        showRecurrentEntities(designatedSet);
    }

    static void showRecurrentEntities(Object[] arr) {
        Map<Integer, Integer> countMap = new HashMap<>();

        for (Object obj : arr) {
            if (obj instanceof Integer) {
                int num = (Integer) obj;
                countMap.put(num, countMap.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
            } else {
                System.err.println("Invalid data type found: " + obj);
            }
        }

        // Display the counts of recurrent entities
        boolean foundRecurrent = false;
        for (Map.Entry<Integer, Integer> entry : countMap.entrySet()) {
            if (entry.getValue() > 1) {
                System.out.println(entry.getKey() + " appears " + entry.getValue() + " times");
                foundRecurrent = true;
            }
        }

        if (!foundRecurrent) {
            System.out.println("No recurrent entities found.");
        }
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
